column6: I may be completely off base on this, so hopefully this starts some dialogue. In looking at the data found here: https://gis.cdc.gov/grasp/covidnet/COVID19_5.html It appears that the COVID hospitalization for the last 4 respective weeks are: 2,315, 2,115, 1,749, and 1,348 respectively, with an average decrease of 16.3% per week. Is this number incomplete? Based on the crowd forecast this seems WAY off, but Iâ€™d rather have a lively debate/conversation about it then just guess or misunderstand the data.
Cases are increasing but not as much as what we think
Reflects current trend lines and short time to close of forecast.

Because it is pediatric cases and not general covid cases, I think there will be a significantly less amount. However, because kids are starting to go back to school in some areas, this would cause a slightly higher amount of kids affected.
The decline has significantly flattened out, at about 33k and looks to be holding pretty steady.
Daily average is 4728, which would put a week at 33k. It has also been decreasing.
At about 34k currently and the decline seems to have slowed.
Data from same source is being plotted on ourworldindata.org[1]. Hospitalizations decreased 31% over last 2 week. Same rate of decrease over next 2 weeks will put the number at ~ 22k
A couple days ago, there were 37,000 hospitals, so with more people getting vaccinated, I'm hoping the number will stay close to and be hopefully below 37,000.

From the first two waves' experience, eight weeks after peaking (early January 2021) the number of hospital admissions reaches a trough and then remains low on a near constant level for another five to six weeks. The question is, when exactly the rock bottom will be reached, and how deep it goes until then. The second question is, whether mass vaccination will by then have achieved their target of protecting all vulnerable groups, so it's basically a race of new infections in the 18-49 age group vs vaccination speed. However, it'll be a surprise should the number of new hospital admissions fall below 35k, having in mind that schools as a throwing mill of infections from household to household are back in the equation.
Already down to 37k as of March 6th. So far the pace hasn't slowed as much as I initially thought it was. Things are looking better for lower hospitalizations so I'm weighting downward some more.

Hospitalization tend to drop more slowly than cases--perhaps because as hospitals fill they are less likely to admit some cases. Case rate has leveled off. Expect hospitalizations to behave similarly. Most recent data was a over 43,000 (including children).

43k as of 2/27. These may lag cases slightly, and it looks like the rate of decline has been slowing down a bit lately. I think due to a pretty high rate of vaccinations among the elderly these will continue to decline over time.
